Palinuro) e quella dell'anima; ora, Iacopo e Buonconte parlano del corpo
con quel senso di nostalgia sopra precisato, ma senza dramma, il che
"contrasts sharply with Palinurus' restlessness" (C.A. Cioffi, "Fame,
Prayer and Politics": ^Dante Studies~, 1992, p. 188). Mentre Palinuro
chiede onori funebri, Buonconte chiede solo preghiere: in tal modo "Dante
rewrites the Virgilian model". "Also significant is the difference
between Buonconte's unknown tomb and the place given the ^aeternum
... nomen~ of Palinurus (^Aen~. VI.381). In choosing to emphasize the
namelessness of the place where Buonconte dies (v. 97), Dante continues
to undermine the pagan notion of fame [...] In effect, he shifts from
the Virgilian character's obsession with the perpetuation of his ^nomen~
in an obscure cape to Buonconte's humble utterance of the |nome di Maria~
(v.  101), the one name that truly ensures the salvation of Buonconte's
soul. In the ^Aeneid~, the welfare of Palinuro's shade depends on the
conditions of his physical body. In ^Purgatorio~ V, as in the canto of
Manfred, Dante severs the connection between what happens to the spirit
and what happens to the flesh. Buonconte makes the point by referring
dismissively to his corporeality: |caddi, e rimase la mia carne sola~
(v. 102). His soul, the true locus of identity and of the eternality
(|di costui l'etterno~: v. 106), is taken by God's angel because of the
contrition manifested |per una lagrimetta~ (v. 107). Here Dante contrasts
the infinite and unfathomable mercy of God with the pitiless and obstinate
will of the gods toward Palinurus" (C.A. Cioffi, ^Op.  cit~., p. 191).

